Flipper is a program for computing the action of mapping classes on curves 
and laminations on a punctured surface using ideal triangulation coordinates. 
Eventually it will also be able to construct the canonical triangulation of 
the surface bundle associated to pseudo-Anosov mapping class.

Flipper is available from:
	https://bitbucket.org/Mark_Bell/flipper

You can download the latest version directly from:
	https://bitbucket.org/Mark_Bell/flipper/get/default.zip

Alternatively, you can clone the mercurial repository directly:
	hg clone https://bitbucket.org/Mark_Bell/Flipper

For more information about installing and using Flipper see "A users guide to 
Flipper" located at:
	./Docs/Flipper.pdf

If you find Flipper useful in your research, please consider citing it. A suggested reference is:
	Mark Bell. Flipper (Computer Software).
	https://bitbucket.org/Mark_Bell/flipper/, 2013–2014. Version 0.1.1.
or the BibTeX entry:
	@Misc{Flipper,
		author = {Bell, Mark},
		title = {Flipper (Computer Software)},
		howpublished = {\url{https://bitbucket.org/Mark_Bell/flipper/}},
		year = {2013--2014},
		note = {Version 0.1.0}
	}

Quick install, test and start as a Python module:
> python setup.py install --user
> python setup.py test
> python -m Flipper.app

Quick install, test and start as a Sage module:
> sage -python setup.py install --user
> sage -python setup.py test
> sage -python -m Flipper.app
